AGI - The race to announce the record made a nice slide to the Indian weather office that a few hours after proclaiming that the mercury colony had touched 52,9 degrees in a suburb of Delhi was forced to rectify by blaming a faulty sensor. The incident has emphasized the fundamental importance of checking temperature readings, in particular to monitor and understand how the climate is changing - and respond accordingly. The United Nations World Meteorological Organization is responsible for certification of global, continental and hemisphere temperature records. It is based in Geneva and maintains a global archive of extreme weather and weather conditions, records data relating to temperature, pressure, precipitation, hail, aridity, wind, lightning and weather conditions. Its long verification process takes months and even years of careful scientific control and sometimes finds faults of measurement and errors of the equipment that decay the declared data. The OMM first contactes the national weather service of the country concerned and the organization that has registered the alleged <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-30/india-caldo-record-new-delhi-colpa-di-un-sensore-guasto-26573921/">record</a> to obtain raw data. This includes details of the exact reading position, the equipment used, its calibration and regional weather conditions at that time. &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
A first evaluation is carried out by the OMM Climatology Commission and by Randall Cerveny, rapporteur of the organization for extreme weather and weather conditions, who manages the document archive. An international group of atmospheric scientists then examines raw data and provides Cerveny, professor of geographic science at Arizona State University, recommendations for his final verdict. In 2005, while watching American news coverage in the wake of hurricane Katrina's destruction in New Orleans, Cerveny was hit by television presenters who repeatedly called him the worst hurricane of all time. He knew it was not true: while Katrina caused 1,800 deaths, a tropical cyclone in 1970 had killed about 300,000 in what is now Bangladesh.&nbsp; It was then that Cerveny wrote a scientific article asking for an official global record database. And in 2007, OMM asked him to create one, to maintain world, hemisphere and regional records for particular extreme weather events.
<h2>A what it is necessary to identify records
According to the OMM, knowing the extreme weather and weather conditions is essential to determine exactly how quickly and how rapidly the world climate is changing. Information is also important for health planning and civil engineering. For example, architects must know the maximum speed of the wind possible when designing a bridge. Another reason to maintain the record database was to advance the <a href="https://www.agi.it/scienza/">scienza</a> and help the media to put forward weather events. The OMM also reviews documents prior to 2007 and sometimes deletes them. The best known case is that of the world record temperature of 58 degrees measured in 1922 in El Azizia, in current Libya. Following a two-year investigation conducted under dangerous conditions during the 2011 Libyan revolution, the record was invalidated due to five unreliable values, including potentially problematic instrumentation and "an inexperienced observer".
&nbsp;
Since then, the 56.7 degrees recorded on July 10, 1913 in Furnace Creek, in Death Valley in the United States, hold the world record of heat. In July 2021, the OMM recognized a new high temperature record for the Antarctic continent, confirming a reading of 18.3 C carried out at the Argentine research station Esperanza, in the Antarctic Peninsula, on 6 February 2020. But above all, the OMM rejected an even higher temperature reading of 20.75 C (69.35) reported on 9 February 2020 at an automated Brazilian monitoring station on the nearby Seymour island: an artisanal anti-radiation shield led to a demonstrable thermal polarization error for the permafrost monitor's air temperature sensor, making its reading of the record unsuitable.&nbsp;&nbsp;

